Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 0d9462115c53d478ed757ca4a3cccd0acf593781
I also took a look at the previous related clearLog commit at  https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/36796 but didn't notice a specific reason to not use DeleteAll.

Summary of feedback from Ed via discord, which I will look into addressing:

"All collections have ClearLog actions attached to them, so either they [(DeleteAll in this case)] need to be required in PDI, or we need to check to see if that object has a ClearLog interface before we populate the action.
I'm honestly ok with either, probably a preference for the later, because I suspect we'll have logs in the future that don't allow clearing.
or are read-only"

Discord thread: https://discord.com/channels/775381525260664832/855566794994221117/1001231412986388661

- Added comment in PDI recommending dump managers to implement DeleteAll  (https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/commit/7311efe3cbabaa6e86c3b33997cb6ef48e52180b)
- Added patchset 3 to check for DeleteAll interface when deciding whether to populate the ClearLog action for a dump LogService.
Just to double check: are all the dump managers implementing the DeleteAll interface?

Yes, it's implemented by the base dump manager (see https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-debug-collector/blob/master/dump_manager.hpp#L17 and https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-debug-collector/blob/master/dump_manager.cpp#L13), and the BMC/FaultLog/System dump managers all inherit from the base dump manager.

Is this the right way to check if "/xyz/openbmc_project/dump/" + dumpTypeLowerCopy" implement "DeleteAll"?

We already hardcode where the corresponding object is, right? Can we just Introspect that object and check the interfaces? This saves a mapper call
Using introspect sounds doable, I will work on the change.
Can we unit test this method?
No longer applicable after reverting back to using the mapper in getDumpServiceInfo().

This methods existence doesn't align with our uses of DBus.  Please take a look at other examples for how to determine the existence of an interface.

If you think that parsing XML is a better option, I'm happy to have that discussion outside of adding a new feature, but I suspect that wasn't your intent here.
This is from the other thread. Claire is using ObjectMapper initially, and I asked whether it's possible to introspect the object directly to save an ObjectMapper call.
Why would we do that?  There are very good reasons why we don't as a general practice.

I asked why first 😊  Why would we do this, when we don't do it anywhere else?

At a minimum, we know the existing code patterns work for building reasonably reliable Redfish endpoints.  As a start, we shouldn't change without reason, so the onus is on the change-maker to talk about (documented in the developing guide) why we're changing.


Off the top of my head: 
1. It duplicates code already in the mapper.
2. it has race conditions that have already been solved and debugged in the matter.
3. It imposes a hard requirement on tinyxml in bmcweb, whereas previously, only dbus-rest required it.
4. It doesn't work properly if the interfaces are split between two daemons.
5. (guessing) it is most likely slower, given the XML payload is going to be several orders of magnitude larger than the mapper response.

Also, from DBUS_USAGE.md

"There are interfaces for which there is an expectation that there will only ever be one producer in the project (ex bmc networking, user management). In these cases, it is desirable to call the daemon by well known name directly. Bmcweb APIs should call the mapper in cases where it's reasonably expected that multiple implementations exist (ex, CPU management, Sensors)."

Reverted back to using the mapper (like patchset 3).

Ed, thanks for the explanation. Do you have any examples to share that could help illustrate #2 (race conditions related to introspection) and #5 (interfaces split between two daemons) for my understanding?
I am good in this thread.
Can do this outside the loop.
Removing tests are unfortunate but the function under test now has a dbus call. We don't yet have a good way to unit test that.
